## Nix Builder Setup

NixOS VM images are built using the Nix package manager, which requires a Linux
execution environment for the build sandbox.

{% if nix_builder.type == 'local' %}
{# --- Local (Linux workstation) --- #}

Your workstation is configured as a Linux system (`nix_builder.type: local`).
No additional builder setup is needed — Nix builds Linux derivations natively.

**Verify:**
```bash
framework/scripts/setup-nix-builder.sh --verify
```
- [ ] Script reports "Nix builder: local. No setup needed."
- [ ] Test build succeeds

{% elif nix_builder.type == 'linux-builder' %}
{# --- Nix-managed local VM (macOS) --- #}

Your workstation is macOS. Nix will manage a lightweight NixOS VM locally
to provide a Linux build environment. This is transparent — `nix build`
commands delegate to the VM automatically.

### Recommended nix-darwin Configuration

Add to your nix-darwin configuration (e.g., `~/.config/nix-darwin/flake.nix`):

```nix
nix.linux-builder = {
  enable = true;
  ephemeral = true;     # Recreate disk on restart (required for config changes)
  maxJobs = 4;
  config = {
    virtualisation = {
      darwin-builder = {
        diskSize = 80 * 1024;    # 80GB — must fit the largest image closure
        memorySize = {{ (nix_builder.memory_gb | default(24)) }} * 1024;
      };
      cores = {{ nix_builder.cpus | default(8) }};
    };
  };
};
```

Then run: `darwin-rebuild switch`

> **Why these settings matter:** The default linux-builder has 1 core, 3 GB
> RAM, and a small writable disk overlay (~1GB). NixOS image builds (especially
> GitLab at ~6.4GB) require significantly more resources and disk space.

> **Important:** Do NOT run `nix-collect-garbage` on the host while actively
> using the builder. The host's `/nix/store` is the builder's read-only cache.
> GC-ing it forces the builder to re-download paths into its small writable
> overlay, which can overflow on large builds. If you must GC, repopulate
> the shared closure afterward:
> `nix build .#packages.x86_64-linux.gitlab-image --no-link`

**Setup:**
```bash
framework/scripts/setup-nix-builder.sh
```

This script will:
- Detect whether you're using nix-darwin or standalone Nix
- Generate `~/.nix-builder/start-builder.sh` with correct QEMU_OPTS
- Write `/etc/nix/machines` with maxJobs={{ nix_builder.cpus | default(8) }}
- Start the builder VM and verify it can compile a Linux derivation

{# Note: don't document the internal nix-darwin vs standalone distinction here.
   The script handles detection and prints the right instructions. Documenting
   both paths in the bringup guide would violate the deduplication principle. #}

**Verify:**
```bash
framework/scripts/setup-nix-builder.sh --verify
# Test that the builder can build a real derivation:
nix build --impure --expr '(import <nixpkgs> { system = "x86_64-linux"; }).hello' --no-link
```
- [ ] Builder VM is running with correct resources
- [ ] Test build completes without error

**Restart the builder** if it breaks or after a reboot:
```bash
framework/scripts/setup-nix-builder.sh --stop
framework/scripts/setup-nix-builder.sh --start
```

{% elif nix_builder.type == 'remote' %}
{# --- Remote builder via SSH --- #}

Your workstation delegates NixOS image builds to a remote Linux host over SSH.

**Remote host:** `{{ nix_builder.remote_user }}@{{ nix_builder.remote_host }}`
**SSH key:** `{{ nix_builder.remote_ssh_key }}`

### Step 1: Install Nix on the remote host

SSH to the remote host and install the Nix package manager:

```bash
ssh {{ nix_builder.remote_user }}@{{ nix_builder.remote_host }}
curl -L https://nixos.org/nix/install | sh --daemon
```

After installation, verify (still on the remote host):
```bash
nix --version
```
- [ ] Nix is installed and reports a version number

> **Note:** This installs the Nix *package manager* on the existing OS
> (e.g., Debian on a Proxmox node). It does NOT convert the host to NixOS.
> Nix installs entirely under `/nix/` and does not modify system packages.

Log out of the remote host.

### Step 2: Configure local workstation

Run the setup script from your workstation:
```bash
framework/scripts/setup-nix-builder.sh
```

This script will:
- Verify SSH connectivity to `{{ nix_builder.remote_host }}`
- Verify Nix is installed on the remote host
- Add the remote builder to `/etc/nix/machines`
- Configure `nix.conf` for remote builds
- Restart nix-daemon

### Verify

```bash
framework/scripts/setup-nix-builder.sh --verify
```
- [ ] SSH to `{{ nix_builder.remote_host }}` succeeds without password prompt
- [ ] Remote host has Nix installed
- [ ] Test build of a Linux derivation succeeds
- [ ] `nix build --impure --expr '(import <nixpkgs> { system = "x86_64-linux"; }).hello' --no-link` completes without error

> **Cleanup (for later):** Once CI/CD handles image builds (Step 7), the remote
> builder is no longer needed. To remove Nix from the remote host:
> `ssh {{ nix_builder.remote_user }}@{{ nix_builder.remote_host }} "rm -rf /nix && rm -rf /etc/nix"`

